# Task 4: Decision Trees for Classification

## Objective
Build a decision tree classifier to predict a categorical outcome
(species of flowers).

## Dataset
Iris dataset (150 samples, 4 features, 3 species) — built into scikit-learn

## Steps Performed
- Trained an initial unpruned decision tree (max depth = 5)
- Visualized the full tree structure
- Pruned the tree by testing max_depth values from 1 to 5
- Selected the best-performing depth based on test accuracy and F1-score
- Evaluated final model using classification report and confusion matrix

## Results
- Unpruned tree (depth=5): 93.3% accuracy
- Pruned tree (depth=3): 96.7% accuracy, 0.967 weighted F1-score

## Key Insight
The pruned tree (max_depth=3) outperformed the unpruned tree, confirming
that the extra depth in the full tree was overfitting rather than adding
real predictive value. Setosa is perfectly separable from the other two
species. The only misclassification occurs between versicolor and
virginica, a well-documented hard case for this dataset due to overlapping
petal measurements.

## Tools Used
Python, pandas, scikit-learn, matplotlib, NumPy

